d": false, "mention": "cholesterol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999298095703125, "span": {"begin": 2718, "end": 2729}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "immature and adult Leydig cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8806673288345337, "span": {"begin": 2776, "end": 2807}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013739"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "testosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992172718048096, "span": {"begin": 2829, "end": 2841}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "immature", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.5269767045974731, "span": {"begin": 2875, "end": 2883}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "immature and adult Leydig cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.620505690574646, "span": {"begin": 2875, "end": 2906}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:17563"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Phthalate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.998506486415863, "span": {"begin": 2983, "end": 2992}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rat", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9889698028564453, "span": {"begin": 3010, "end": 3013}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6770", "2984"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "mRNA StAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.952597439289093, "span": {"begin": 3055, "end": 3064}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003993"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Dibutyl phthalate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991601705551147, "span": {"begin": 3306, "end": 3323}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:35861"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DBP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996695518493652, "span": {"begin": 3325, "end": 3328}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004051"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Di-2-ethylhexyl phthalate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996224045753479, "span": {"begin": 3331, "end": 3356}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004051"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DEHP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999426007270813, "span": {"begin": 3358, "end": 3362}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016599"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mono(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9921678900718689, "span": {"begin": 3365, "end": 3393}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016599"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MEHP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987503290176392, "span": {"begin": 3395, "end": 3399}}], "text": "The role of StAR in cholesterol transport becomes evident in individuals with StAR deficiency. These individuals have a condition called congenital lipoid adrenal hyperplasia (LCAH), characterized by an inability to synthesize steroids and accumulated fatty deposits in steroidogenic cells, attributed to the failure of cholesterol transport to mitochondria (Stocco, 2002). These individuals can have underdeveloped genitalia and may require lifelong hormone replacement therapy. Additionally, mouse StAR knock-out studies treated with corticosteroid replacement demonstrate the same phenotype (Caron et al., 1997; Hasegawa et al., 2000).  Down-regulation of StAR and impaired steroidogenesis was reported upon exposure to phthalates i.a. (Barlow et al. 2003), (Borch et al. 2006), for details see Table 1.           &nbsp;    &nbsp;    &nbsp;        KE: StAR, decrease            KE: Cholesterol transport, decrease        &nbsp;    &nbsp;              Compound            Species            Effect level        &nbsp;    &nbsp;        Details            References                  Phthalate (DBP)            rat            LOEL=500 mg/kg/day            mRNA StAR decrease (by ~34%)            reduced Leydig cell lipid content        &nbsp;        (Barlow et al. 2003)                  Phthalate (DBP)            rat            LOEL=500 mg/kg/day (GD12-19)        &nbsp;        decrease uptake of cholesterol Leydig cell mitochondria            decreased testosterone, decreased expression of scavenger receptor B1, P450(SCC), steroidogenic acute regulatory protein, and cytochrome p450c17            (Thompson, Ross, and Gaido 2004)                  Phthalate (DBP)            rat            LOEL=500 mg/kg            mRNA and protein StAR decrease        &nbsp;        1 dose, Time course analysis (0,5,1,2,3,6,12,18, 24h killed at GD), decreased testosterone in foetal testis            (Thompson et al. 2005)                  Phthalate (DEHP)            rat            LOEL=300&nbsp;mg/ kg/day     &nbsp;            mRNA StAR decrease            &nbsp;            dose-dependently reduced StAR, TSOP mRNA (GD 21 testes), also on protein levels in Leydig cells     &nbsp;            (Borch et al. 2006)                  Phthalate (DBP)            rat            LOEL=500 mg/kg/day, (GD12 to 21)            mRNA StAR decrease            &nbsp;            Testes examined GD 16, 19, and 21, cytochrome P450 side chain cleavage, cytochrome P450c17, decrease.     Testicular testosterone and androstenedione decreased (GD 19 and 21)            (Shultz 2001)                  Phthalate (MEHP)            rat            LOEC=250&nbsp;&mu;M            protein StAR decrease (immature and adult Leydig cells)            cholesterol transport, decrease (into the mitochondria of immature and adult Leydig cells            decreased testosterone by approximately 60%, in vitro ( immature and adult Leydig cells)            (Svechnikov, Svechnikova, and S&ouml;der 2008)                  Phthalate (DBP)            rat            LOEL=500 mg/kg/day            mRNA StAR decrease            &nbsp;            GD 12 -20, examinations on GD20            (Johnson et al. 2011)            Table 1 Summary table of empirical support for this KER. LOEC-lowest effect concentration, LOEL- lowest observed effect level, Dibutyl phthalate (DBP), Di-2-ethylhexyl phthalate (DEHP), mono(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (MEHP).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:31:51 +0000 2026"}